In [3]:
def _centered(arr, newsize):
    # Return the center newsize portion of the array.
    newsize = np.asarray(newsize)
    currsize = np.array(arr.shape)
    startind = (currsize - newsize) // 2
    endind = startind + newsize
    myslice = [slice(startind[k], endind[k]) for k in range(len(endind))]
    return arr[tuple(myslice)]

scipy.signal.signaltools._centered = _centered

ax1.set_title('Difference ones')

In [51]:
# Taking 2 difference to check the time series behaviour

diff2=data['close '].diff().diff().dropna()
fig,(ax1,ax2)=plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(16,5))
ax1.plot(diff2)
ax1.set_title('Difference ones')
plot_acf(diff2,ax=ax2)
plt.show()

Comments:¶

  1. Not much change when we take difference 1 or 2.
  2. We dont know how many differences we should take to make time series stationary.
  3. Instead of doing it manually, we can use the pmdarima package to get the number of differencing.
  4. This automated package gives us best values.
  5. This package uses ADF test to check stationarity.
